 name=\"ECC\">All appearance(s) in [[UEFA Champions League|European Champion Clubs' Cup]]</ref>||1||colspan=2|\u2014||29||5\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!102!!59!!14!!5!!2!!1!!colspan=2|\u2014!!118!!65\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Servette FC|Servette]]\n|[[1961\u201362 Nationalliga A|1961-62]]\n|[[Swiss Super League|Nationalliga A]]\n|19||13||0||0||3<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"ECC\"/>||2||colspan=2|\u2014||22||15\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!19!!13!!0!!0!!3!!2!!colspan=2|\u2014!!22!!15\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"|[[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne|Saint-\u00c9tienne]]\n|[[1962\u201363 French Division 2|1962-63]]\n|[[French Division 2|Division 2]]\n|20||14||4||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||24||14\n|-\n|[[1963\u201364 French Division 1|1963-64]]\n|rowspan=5| [[French Division 1|Division 1]]\n|34||16||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||35||16\n|-\n|[[1964\u201365 French Division 1|1964-65]]\n|32||8||5||0||2<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"ECC\"/>||1||colspan=2|\u2014||39||9\n|-\n|[[1965\u201366 French Division 1|1965-66]]\n|38||21||1||1||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||39||22\n|-\n|[[1966\u201367 French Division 1|1966-67]]\n|38||12||2||1||colspan=2|\u2014||1<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"CS\">Appearance in [[Troph\u00e9e des Champions|Challenge des champions]]</ref>||1||41||14\n|-\n|[[1967\u201368 French Division 1|1967-68]]\n|30||7||5||5||4<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"ECC\"/>||0||colspan=2|\u2014||39||12\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!192!!78!!18!!7!!6!!1!!1!!1!!217!!87\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[SC Bastia|Bastia]]\n|[[1968\u201369 French Division 1|1968-69]]\n|rowspan=2| [[French Division 1|Division 1]]\n|33||13||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||34||13\n|-\n|[[1969\u201370 French Division 1|1969-70]]\n|34||7||9||2||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||43||9\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!67!!20!!10!!2!!colspan=2|\u2014!!colspan=2|\u2014!!77!!22\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career Total\n!380!!170!!42!!14!!11!!4!!1!!1!!434!!189\n|}\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Clubs===\n; [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne|Saint-\u00c9tienne]]:\n* [[French Division 1]] (4): [[1956\u201357 French Division 1|1956\u201357]], [[1963\u201364 French Division 1|1963\u201364]], [[1966\u201367 French Division 1|1966\u201367]], [[1967\u201368 French Division 1|1967\u201368]]\n* [[Coupe de France]] (1): [[1968 Coupe de France Final|1968]]\n* [[Troph\u00e9e des Champions]] (2): [[Troph\u00e9e des Champions|1957]], [[Troph\u00e9e des Champions|1967]]\n* [[Coupe Charles Drago]] (2): [[Coupe Charles Drago|1955]], [[Coupe Charles Drago|1958]]\n\n; [[Servette FC|Servette]]:\n* [[Swiss Super League|Nationalliga A]] (1): [[1967\u201368 Nationalliga A|1961\u201362]]\n\n===National team===\n* Win the [[Military World Cup]] in 1957 with the [[France military national football team|French military team]]\n\n===Managerial===\n* Win the gold medal in the [[1975 Mediterranean Games]] with [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]]\n* Win the gold medal in the [[1978 All-Africa Games]] with [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]]\n* Participation in [[1982 FIFA World Cup]] with [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]]\n\n===Personal===\n* Best goalscorer of [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne]] with 192 goals\n\n== Legacy ==\nIn the middle of the [[Algerian War]], on April 13th 1958, ten of the most well-known France-Based professional football (soccer) players fled from France to go and play for their new [[FLN football team]]. This team was created from the [[National Liberation Front (Algeria)]]. One of these 10 players was Rachid Mekhloufi. Rachid, \"abandoned the French team preparing for the World Cup Finals in Sweden and instantly became an Algerian national symbol.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Alegi, Peter.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/794698908|title=African Soccerscapes : How a Continent Changed the World's Game|date=2010|publisher=Ohio University Press|isbn=978-0-89680-472-2|location=Athens|oclc=794698908}}</ref> By the summer, more and more France-based Algerians came to join the original ten who fled. Rachid and his fellow teammates wanted to show the French people the serious war that was going on in Algeria. Many of them did not realize the extent of the war going on, and when ten high-caliber players lef, the French citizens had to wonder and figure out the exact reason why-especially when a few of the footballers were preparing for the World Cup Finals. At the same time, both Rachid and his teammates gave a sense of nationalism to the Citizens of Algeria during their efforts in the War. Mekhloufi (and many others) sacrificed their careers by playing in less competitive environments with lesser demanding training regimes. Mekhloufi is quoted saying \"I had lost the taste for effort, the necessary fight\" when asked about playing political football<ref name=\":0\" /> . The France-based footballers were a source of nationhood for Algerians, especially in times such as Algeria's 2-0 victory over West Germany in Algiers on January 1, 1964 where Mekhloufi and [[Mustapha Zitouni]] starred.\n\nAfter the disbanding of the FLN in 1962, Mekhloufi returned to play in France. Later on Mekhloufi would come back to manage and coach the Algeria National Football team.\n<br />\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fff.fr/servfff/historique/historique.php?id=MEKHLOUFI%20Rachid Profile]\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.panthere-verte.com/asse-joueur-353-rachid-mekhloufi.html |title=Profile |access-date=2007-06-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928042006/http://www.panthere-verte.com/asse-joueur-353-rachid-mekhloufi.html |archive-date=2007-09-28 |url-status=dead }}\n*[http://www.anciensverts.com/lettre.php?lettre=m Short bio]\n*[http://www.afrik.com/article7733.html Another bio]\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.pari-et-gagne.com/joueur/rachid_mekhloufi.html |title=Rachid Mekhloufi at pari-et-gagne.com |access-date=2011-08-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208225508/http://www.pari-et-gagne.com/joueur/rachid_mekhloufi.html |archive-date=2012-02-08 |url-status=bot: unknown }}\n*{{FootballDatabase.eu|37274}}\n\n{{SC Bastia managers}}\n{{Algeria Squad 1982 World Cup}}\n{{Algeria national football team managers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mekhloufi, Rachid}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French footballers]]\n[[Category:France international footballers]]\n[[Category:Algerian footballers]]\n[[Category:Algeria international footballers]]\n[[Category:Algerian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Dual internationalists (football)]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:AS Saint-\u00c9tienne players]]\n[[Category:Servette FC players]]\n[[Category:SC Bastia players]]\n[[Category:French people of Algerian descent]]\n[[Category:Algerian football managers]]\n[[Category:SC Bastia managers]]\n[[Category:1982 FIFA World Cup managers]]\n[[Category:Footballers from S\u00e9tif]]\n[[Category:Algeria national football team managers]]\n[[Category:Algerian expatriate sportspeople in Tunisia]]\n[[Category:USM S\u00e9tif players]]\n[[Category:Algerian expatriate sportspeople in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Algerian expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:FLN football team players]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Rachid Mekhloufi\n| image = Rachid Mekhloufi (cropped).jpg\n| fullname = Rachid Mekhloufi\n| height = 1.68 m\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1936|8|12}}\n| birth_place = [[S\u00e9tif]], [[French Algeria]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| position = [[Striker (football)|Striker]]\n| youthyears1 = 19??\u20131954\n| youthclubs1 = [[USM S\u00e9tif]]\n| years1 = 1954\u20131958\n| years2 = 1961\u20131962\n| years3 = 1962\u20131968\n| years4 = 1968\u20131970\n| clubs1 = [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne|S