ate=24 October 2017 | author=Freedland, Jonathan}}</ref>\n\n;Television documentaries\n* ''Landscape and Memory'' (1995), in five parts\n* ''Rembrandt: The Public Eye and the Private Gaze'' (1995)\n* ''[[A History of Britain (TV series)|A History of Britain by Simon Schama]]'' \u2013 BBC (2000), in 15 parts\n* ''Murder at Harvard'' \u2013 PBS (2003)\n* ''[[Rough Crossings]]'' \u2013 BBC (2005)\n* ''[[Simon Schama's Power of Art]]'' \u2013 BBC (2006), in eight parts\n* ''[[The American Future: A History]]'' \u2013 BBC (2008), in four parts\n* ''Simon Schama's John Donne'' \u2013 BBC (2009)\n* ''Simon Schama's: Obama's America'' \u2013 BBC (2009)\n* ''Simon Schama's Shakespeare'' \u2013 BBC (2012)\n* ''[[The Story of the Jews]]'' \u2013 BBC (2013), in five parts\n* ''Schama on Rembrandt: Masterpieces of the Late Years'' \u2013 BBC (2014)\n* ''The Face of Britain by Simon Schama'' \u2013 BBC (2015), in five parts\n* ''[[Civilisations (TV series)|Civilisations]]'' \u2013 BBC (2018), five of nine parts\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.columbia.edu/cu/arthistory/html/dept_faculty_schama.html Columbia Art History faculty page]\n* {{C-SPAN|Simon Schama}}\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/culture/simon-schama Simon Schama | Culture | The Guardian]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/simonschama Simon Schama | The Guardian]\n*[https://www.newstatesman.com/node/152276 Simon Schama | New Statesman]\n*[https://www.spectator.co.uk/tag/simon-schama/ Simon Schama] on ''[[The Spectator]]''\n\n{{Wolfson History Prize Winners}}\n{{FBA 2015}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schama, Simon}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century English historians]]\n[[Category:21st-century English historians]]\n[[Category:21st-century English writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British expatriate academics in the United States]]\n[[Category:Columbia University faculty]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Corresponding Fellows of the British Academy]]\n[[Category:English art historians]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:English people of Lithuanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Romanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Turkish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English television presenters]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Brasenose College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Christ's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:Historians of the Dutch Republic]]\n[[Category:Historians of the French Revolution]]\n[[Category:Historians of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Jewish historians]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:NCR Book Award winners]]\n[[Category:People educated at Haberdashers' Aske's Boys' School]]\n[[Category:People from Briarcliff Manor, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Marylebone]]\n[[Category:People from Southend-on-Sea]]\n[[Category:Rembrandt scholars]]\n[[Category:Scholars of Dutch art]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:Clearly referencing anti-zionism so fits this section", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simon_Schama"}
{"title_page": "Cupressus lusitanica", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of plant}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Mexican Cypress.jpg\n| image_caption = A mature ''Cupressus lusitanica''\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn/>\n| genus = Cupressus\n| species = lusitanica\n| authority = [[Philip Miller|Mill.]]\n| synonyms_ref = <ref>{{ThePlantList |id=kew-2748717 |taxon=Cupressus lusitanica |authority=Mill.}}</ref>\n| synonyms = {{collapsible list|bullets = true\n|title=<small>Synonymy</small>\n|''Callitropsis lusitanica'' <small>(Mill.) D.P.Little</small>\n|''Cupressus coulteri'' <small>J.Forbes</small>\n|''Cupressus excelsa'' <small>J.Scott ex Carri\u00e8re</small>\n|''Cupressus glauca]'' <small>Lam.</small>\n|''Cupressus karwinskiana'' <small>Regel</small>\n|''Cupressus lindleyi'' <small>Klotzsch ex Endl.</small>\n|''Cupressus mexicana'' <small>K.Koch</small>\n|''Cupressus pendula'' <small>L'H\u00e9r. 1785 not Thunb. 1784</small>\n|''Cupressus sinensis'' <small>J.Lee ex Gord.</small>\n|''Cupressus thurifera'' <small>Lindl.</small>\n|''Cupressus uhdeana'' <small>Gordon ex Carri\u00e8re</small>\n|''Hesperocyparis lindleyi'' <small>(Klotzsch ex Endl.) Silba</small>\n|''Hesperocyparis lusitanica'' <small>(Mill.) Bartel</small>\n|''Juniperus uhdeana'' <small>Gordon</small>\n|''Neocupressus lusitanica'' <small>(Mill.) de Laub.</small>\n|''Callitropsis benthamii'' <small>(Endl.) D.P.Little</small>\n|''Cupressus benthamii'' <small>Endl.</small>\n|''Cupressus ehrenbergii'' <small>Kunze</small>\n|''Cupressus knightiana'' <small>Perry ex Gordon</small>\n|''Hesperocyparis benthamii'' <small>(Endl.) Bartel</small>\n|plus many more names at the level of subspecies, variety, or form\n}}}}\n[[File:Cupressus lusitanica.jpg|thumb|right|''Cupressus lusitanica'' var. ''lusitanica'' foliage and cones]]\n[[File:Cupressus lusitanica00.jpg|thumb|<center>''Cupressus lusitanica'' section</center>]]\n\n'''''Cupressus lusitanica''''', ('''cedro blanco'''; '''teotlate''', distinctive names used in Mexico); cedro blanco means white cedar and is also known as '''Mexican white cedar''' or '''cedar-of-Goa''', is a species of [[Cupressaceae|cypress]] native to [[Mexico]] and [[Central America]] ([[Guatemala]], [[El Salvador]] and [[Honduras]]). It has also been introduced to [[Belize]], [[Costa Rica]] and [[Nicaragua]], growing at {{convert|1200|-|3000|m|ft}} altitude.\n\nThe scientific name ''lusitanica'' (of [[Portugal]]) refers to its very early cultivation there, with plants imported from Mexico to the monastery at [[Bu\u00e7aco]], near [[Coimbra]] in Portugal in about 1634; these trees were already over 130 years old when the species was botanically described by [[Philip Miller|Miller]] in 1768.\n\n__TOC__\n\n==Description==\n''Cupressus lusitanica'' is an [[evergreen]] [[conifer]] tree with a conic to ovoid-conic crown, growing to 40 m tall. The foliage grows in dense sprays, dark green to somewhat yellow-green in colour. The leaves are scale-like, 2\u20135&nbsp;mm long, and produced on rounded (not flattened) shoots. The seed [[conifer cone|cones]] are globose to oblong, 10\u201320&nbsp;mm long, with four to 10 scales, green at first, maturing brown or grey-brown about 25 months after pollination.\n\nThe cones may either open at maturity to release the seeds, or remain closed for several years, only opening after the parent tree is killed in a [[wildfire]], allowing the [[seed]]s to colonise the bare ground exposed by the fire. The male cones are 3\u20134 mm long, and release pollen in late Winter / Early Spring (February\u2013March in the northern hemisphere). In most of its natural environment the rainfall occurs with more quantity in summer.\n\n===Varieties===\nThere are two [[variety (biology)|varieties]], treated as distinct species by some botanists:\n* '''''Cupressus lusitanica'' var. ''lusitanica''''' (syn. ''C. lindleyi'') - '''Mexican cypress''' - Foliage in three-dimensional sprays, with small shoots in two planes. Occurs in lower rainfall areas. ([[Least concern]] species)\n* '''''Cupressus lusitanica'' var. ''benthamii''''' (syn. ''C. benthamii'') - '''Bentham's cypress''' -  Foliage in flattened sprays, with small shoots all in one plane. Occurs in higher rainfall areas. ([[Near Threatened]] species)\n\n==Cultivation and uses==\nFast-growing and drought tolerant, but only slightly frost tolerant, ''Cupressus lusitanica'' has been introduced from Mexico's provenances to different parts of the world. It is widely cultivated, both as an [[ornamental tree]] and for [[timber]] production, in warm, temperate and subtropical regions around the world. Trees have not been selected for cultivation from northern Mexico populations, which have a heavy drought endurance.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Felger |first1=Richard S. |last2=Johnson |first2=Matthew B. |last3=Wilson |first3=Michael F. |date=2001 |title=The trees of Sonora, Mexico |place=New York<!--sic --> |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=0-19-512891-5}}</ref>\n\n===Locations===\nIts cultivation and subsequent [[naturalisation (biology)|naturalisation]] in parts of southern [[Asia]] has caused a degree of confusion with native ''Cupressus'' species in that region; plants sold by nurseries under the names of Asian species such as ''[[Cupressus torulosa]]'' often prove to be this species.\nIt has been planted widely for commercial production: at high altitudes in [[Colombia]] (3300 m), [[Bolivia]], [[Ethiopia]] and [[South Africa]], and near sea level throughout [[New Zealand]]. In [[Colombia]] trees are planted to form [[windbreak]] hedges and for preventing soil erosion on slopes. It has been planted by [[Tanzania]]n mountain farmers for soil preserving and commercial use  since 1990s.<ref>UEDA Gen, ''The Regional System of the Mountain People: Place, Household, and the Communal in Rural Tanzania'' (Japanese language), Tohoku University Press, 2011, Sendai, Japan, pp.348 - 351. (\u4e0a\u7530\u5143\u300e\u5c71\u306e\u6c11\u306e\u5730\u57df\u30b7\u30b9\u30c6\u30e0\u3000\u30bf\u30f3\u30b6\u30cb\u30a2\u8fb2\u6751\u306e\u5834\u6240\u30fb\u4e16\u5e2f\u30fb\u5171\u540c\u6027\u300f\u3001\u6771\u5317\u5927\u5b66\u51fa\u7248\u4f1a\u30012011\u5e74)</ref>\n\nIt has been planted as an ornamental tree near sea level in temperate climates and has done very well in [[Portugal]], [[Buenos Aires Province]] in [[Argentina]]; [[Austin, Texas]] and the [[British Isles]] where it can reach a height of 30 m (90 feet).\n\nIt is being planted in the Argentine province of [[San Luis Province|San Luis]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rama.com.ar/rama_newasp/PaginasIngles/Especies.asp?itemMenu=6&subitemMenu=12\n| title=Mexican conifers in San Luis Province, Argentina}}</ref> [[Argentina]] at 1500 m above sea level with forestation purposes for creating artificial forests in a land originally lacking of them in a very similar climate to that of its origin site.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cedar wood]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn|author=Conifer Specialist Group|year=1998|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/42221/0|title=''Cupressus lusitanica''|access-date=12 May 2006|ref=harv}}</ref>\n}}\n* {{cite book |last=Farjon |first=Aljos |date=2005 |title=A monograph of Cupressaceae and ''Sciadopitys'' |isbn=978-1842460689}}\n* {{cite book |last=Rzedowski |first=J. |date=1978 |title=Vegetaci\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico |place=Distrito Federal, Mexico |isbn=978-9681800024}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Dvorak |first1=W. S. |first2=G. R. |last2=Hodge |first3=E. A. |last3=Guti\u00e9rrez |first4=L. F. |last4=Osorio |first5=F. S. |last5=Malan |first6=T. K. |last6=Stanger. |date=2000 |title=Conservation and Testing of Tropical and Subtropical Forest Species by the CAMCORE Cooperative |publisher=College of Natural Resources, North Carolina State University |place=Raleigh |isbn=978-0620264600}}\n* {{cite book |last=Mart\u00ednez |first=Maximinio |date=1979 |title=Cat\u00e1logo de nombres vulgares y cient\u00edficos de plantas mexicanas |publisher=Fondo de Cultura Econ\u00f3mica |isbn=978-9681600112}}\n* {{cite book |editor-last=Richardson |editor-first=D.M. |date=1998 |title=Ecology and biogeography of ''Pinus'' |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0521789103}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Chandler |first=N.G. |date=1957 |title=Pulpwood plantations in South Africa |journal=Australian Forestry |volume=21 |issue=1 |doi=10.1080/00049158.1957.10675339}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Guti\u00e9rrez |first1=Mill\u00e1n |first2=W. |last2=Ladrach |date=1980 |title=Resultados a tres a\u00f1os de la siembra directa de semillas de ''Cupressus lusitanica'' y ''Pinus patula'' en finca Los Guaduales Departamento del Cauca. Informe de Investigaci\u00f3n 60. |place=Cali, Colombia |publisher=Cart\u00f3n de Colombia S.A.}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://www.conifers.org/cu/cup/lusitanica.htm Gymnosperm Database: ''Cupressus lusitanica'']\n\n{{Cupressaceae}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1308561}}\n\n[[Category:Cupressus|lusitanica]]\n[[Category:Trees of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Trees of Puebla]]\n[[Category:Trees of Veracruz]]\n[[Category:Trees of Central America]]\n[[Category:Least concern plants]]\n[[Category:Trees of temperate climates]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1768]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of Central America]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of North America]]\n[[Category:Drought-tolerant trees]]\n[[Category:Ornamental trees]]\n[[Category:Trees of Guatemala]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of plant}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Mexican Cypress.jpg\n| image_caption = A mature ''Cupressus lusitanica''\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn/>\n| genus = Cupressus\n| species = lusitanica\n| authority = [[Philip Miller|Mill.]]\n| synonyms_ref = <ref>{{ThePlantList |id=kew-2748717 |taxon=Cupressus lusitanica |authority=Mill.}}</ref>\n| synonyms = {{collapsible list|bullets = true\n|title=<small>Synonymy</small>\n|''Callitropsis lusitanica'' <small>(Mill.) D.P.Little</small>\n|''Cupressus coulteri'' <small>J.Forbes</small>\n|''Cupressus excelsa'' <small>J.Scott ex Carri\u00e8re</small>\n|''Cupressus glauca]'' <small>Lam.</small>\n|''Cupressus karwinskiana'' <small>Regel</small>\n|''Cupressus lindleyi'' <small>Klotzsch ex Endl.</small>\n|''Cupressus mexicana'' <small>K.Koch</small>\n|''Cupressus pendula'' <small>L'H\u00e9r. 1785 not Thunb. 1784</small>\n|''Cupressus sinensis'' <small>J.Lee ex Gord.</small>\n|''Cupressus thurifera'' <small>Lindl.</small>\n|''Cupressus uhdeana'' <small>Gordon ex Carri\u00e8re</small>\n|''Hesperocyparis lindleyi'' <small>(Klotzsch ex Endl.) Silba</small>\n|''Hesperocyparis lusitanica'' <small>(Mill.) Bartel</small>\n|''Juniperus uhdeana'' <small>Gordon</small>\n|''Neocupressus lusitanica'' <small>(Mill.) de Laub.</small>\n|''Callitropsis benthamii'' <small>(Endl.) D.P.Little</small>\n|''Cupressus benthamii'' <small>Endl.</small>\n|''Cupressus ehrenbergii'' <small>Kunze</small>\n|''Cupressus knightiana'' <small>Perry ex Gordon</small>\n|''Hesperocyparis benthamii'' <small>(Endl.) Bartel</small>\n|plus many more names at the level of subspecies, variety, or form\n}}}}\n[[File:Cupressus lusitanica.jpg|thumb|right|''Cupressus lusitanica'' var. ''lusitanica'' foliage and cones]]\n[[File:Cupressus lusitanica00.jpg|thumb|<center>''Cupressus lusitanica'' section</center>]]\n\n'''''Cupressus lusitanica''''', ('''cedro blanco'''; '''teotlate''', distinctive names used in Mexico); cedro blanco means white cedar and is also known as '''Mexican white cedar''' or '''cedar-of-Goa''', is a species of [[Cupressaceae|cypress]] native to [[Mexico]] and [[Central America]] ([[Guatemala]], [[El Salvador]] and [[Honduras]]). It has also been introduced to [[Belize]], [[Costa Rica]] and [[Nicaragua]], growing at {{convert|1200|-|3000|m|ft}} altitude.\n\nThe scientific name ''lusitanica'' (of [[Portugal]]) refers to its very early cultivation there, with plants imported from Mexico to the monastery at [[Bu\u00e7aco]], near [[Coimbra]] in Portugal in about 1634; these trees were already over 130 years old when the species was botanically described by [[Philip Miller|Miller]] in 1768.\n\n__TOC__\n\n==Description==\n''Cupressus lusitanica'' is an [[evergreen]] [[conifer]] tree with a conic to ovoid-conic crown, growing to 40 m tall. The foliage grows in dense sprays, dark green to somewhat yellow-green in colour. The leaves are scale-like, 2\u20135&nbsp;mm long, and produced on rounded (not flattened) shoots. The seed [[conifer cone|cones]] are globose to oblong, 10\u201320&nbsp;mm long, with four to 10 scales, green at first, maturing brown or grey-brown about 25 months after pollination.\n\nThe cones may either open at maturity to release the seeds, or remain closed for several years, only opening after the parent tree is killed in a [[wildfire]], allowing the [[seed]]s to colonise the bare ground exposed by the fire. The male cones are 3\u20134&nbsp;mm long, and release pollen in February\u2013March. In most of its natural environment rainfall\noccurs with more quantity in summer.\n\n===Varieties===\nThere are two [[variety (biology)|varieties]], treated as distinct species by some botanists:\n* '''''Cupressus lusitanica'' var. ''lusitanica''''' (syn. ''C. lindleyi'') - '''Mexican cypress''' - Foliage in three-dimensional sprays, with small shoots in two planes. Occurs in lower rainfall areas. ([[Least concern]] species)\n* '''''Cupressus lusitanica'' var. ''benthamii''''' (syn. ''C. benthamii'') - '''Bentham's cypress''' -  Foliage in flattened sprays, with small shoots all in one plane. Occurs in higher rainfall areas. ([[Near Threatened]] species)\n\n==Cultivation and uses==\nFast-growing and drought tolerant, but only slightly frost tolerant, ''Cupressus lusitanica'' has been introduced from Mexico's provenances to different parts of the world. It is widely cultivated, both as an [[ornamental tree]] and for [[timber]] production, in warm, temperate and subtropical regions around the world. Trees have not been selected for cultivation from northern Mexico populations, which have a heavy drought endurance.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Felger |first1=Richard S. |last2=Johnson |first2=Matthew B. |last3=Wilson |first3=Michael F. |date=2001 |title=The trees of Sonora, Mexico |place=New York<!--sic --> |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=0-19-512891-5}}</ref>\n\n===Locations===\nIts cultivation and subsequent [[naturalisation (biology)|naturalisation]] in parts of southern [[Asia]] has caused a degree of confusion with native ''Cupressus'' species in that region; plants sold by nurseries under the names of Asian species such as ''[[Cupressus torulosa]]'' often prove to be this species.\nIt has been planted widely for commercial production: at high altitudes in [[Colombia]] (3300 m), [[Bolivia]], [[Ethiopia]] and [[South Africa]], and near sea level throughout [[New Zealand]]. In [[Colombia]] trees are planted to form [[windbreak]] hedges and for preventing soil erosion on slopes. It has been planted by [[Tanzania]]n mountain farmers for soil preserving and commercial use  since 1990s.<ref>UEDA Gen, ''The Regional System of the Mountain People: Place, Household, and the Communal in Rural Tanzania'' (Japanese language), Tohoku University Press, 2011, Sendai, Japan, pp.348 - 351. (\u4e0a\u7530\u5143\u300e\u5c71\u306e\u6c11\u306e\u5730\u57df\u30b7\u30b9\u30c6\u30e0\u3000\u30bf\u30f3\u30b6\u30cb\u30a2\u8fb2\u6751\u306e\u5834\u6240\u30fb\u4e16\u5e2f\u30fb\u5171\u540c\u6027\u300f\u3001\u6771\u5317\u5927\u5b66\u51fa\u7248\u4f1a\u30012011\u5e74)</ref>\n\nIt has been planted as an ornamental tree near sea level in temperate climates and has done very well in [[Portugal]], [[Buenos Aires Province]] in [[Argentina]]; [[Austin, Texas]] and the [[British Isles]] where it can reach a height of 30 m (90 feet).\n\nIt is being planted in the Argentine province of [[San Luis Province|San Luis]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rama.com.ar/rama_newasp/PaginasIngles/Especies.asp?itemMenu=6&subitemMenu=12\n| title=Mexican conifers in San Luis Province, Argentina}}</ref> [[Argentina]] at 1500 m above sea level with forestation purposes for creating artificial forests in a land originally lacking of them in a very similar climate to that of its origin site.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cedar wood]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn|author=Conifer Specialist Group|year=1998|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/42221/0|title=''Cupressus lusitanica''|access-date=12 May 2006|ref=harv}}</ref>\n}}\n* {{cite book |last=Farjon |first=Aljos |date=2005 |title=A monograph of Cupressaceae and ''Sciadopitys'' |isbn=978-1842460689}}\n* {{cite book |last=Rzedowski |first=J. |date=1978 |title=Vegetaci\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico |place=Distrito Federal, Mexico |isbn=978-9681800024}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Dvorak |first1=W. S. |first2=G. R. |last2=Hodge |first3=E. A. |last3=Guti\u00e9rrez |first4=L. F. |last4=Osorio |first5=F. S. |last5=Malan |first6=T. K. |last6=Stanger. |date=2000 |title=Conservation and Testing of Tropical and Subtropical Forest Species by the CAMCORE Cooperative |publisher=College of Natural Resources, North Carolina State University |place=Raleigh |isbn=978-0620264600}}\n* {{cite book |last=Mart\u00ednez |first=Maximinio |date=1979 |title=Cat\u00e1logo de nombres vulgares y cient\u00edficos de plantas mexicanas |publisher=Fondo de Cultura Econ\u00f3mica |isbn=978-9681600112}}\n* {{cite book |editor-last=Richardson |editor-first=D.M. |date=1998 |title=Ecology and biogeography of ''Pinus'' |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0521789103}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Chandler |first=N.G. |date=1957 |title=Pulpwood plantations in South Africa |journal=Australian Forestry |volume=21 |issue=1 |doi=10.1080/00049158.1957.10675339}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Guti\u00e9rrez |first1=Mill\u00e1n |first2=W. |last2=Ladrach |date=1980 |title=Resultados a tres a\u00f1os de la siembra directa de semillas de ''Cupressus lusitanica'' y ''Pinus patula'' en finca Los Guaduales Departamento del Cauca. Informe de Investigaci\u00f3n 60. |place=Cali, Colombia |publisher=Cart\u00f3n de Colombia S.A.}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://www.conifers.org/cu/cup/lusitanica.htm Gymnosperm Database: ''Cupressus lusitanica'']\n\n{{Cupressaceae}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1308561}}\n\n[[Category:Cupressus|lusitanica]]\n[[Category:Trees of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Trees of Puebla]]\n[[Category:Trees of Veracruz]]\n[[Category:Trees of Central America]]\n[[Category:Least concern plants]]\n[[Category:Trees of temperate climates]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1768]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of Central America]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of North America]]\n[[Category:Drought-tolerant trees]]\n[[Category:Ornamental trees]]\n[[Category:Trees of Guatemala]]\n", "name_user": "RolfP", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDescription", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cupressus_lusitanica"}
